# A worked assembly — one specific poem as a record

The last piece. Individual poems can be records too. The
form record describes the shape. The poem record describes
one instance in that shape. Different type, different
purpose, both useful.

Here's what the Ozymandias sonnet looks like as a poem
record.

```scheme
(record poem
  :name             symbol
  :form             slat-ref              ; -> poem-form
  :speaker          symbol                ; who's talking in the poem
  :beloved-object   (or slat-ref 'none)   ; what the poem is about
  :setup            string                ; brief summary
  :turn             (or string 'none)     ; the volta / kireji / third-line
  :closing          string                ; how it ends
  :sketch           slat-ref              ; the sketch in book-of-words
  :public-domain    boolean)              ; can we quote it?

(poem
  :name          'ozymandias
  :form          'sonnet
  :speaker       'traveler-quoted-by-poet
  :beloved-object 'ruined-statue
  :setup         \"traveler describes a ruined statue in the desert;
                   the pedestal boasts of empire\"
  :turn          \"the shift from the boast to the sand around it —
                   the words say 'despair'; the world says 'gone'\"
  :closing       \"the vast sands stretch far away — deep time as
                   the poem's last image\"
  :sketch        'words-poetry-07-sonnet-ozymandias
  :public-domain #t)
```

## What this composes with

If we have this record and the sonnet form record and the
reasoning record, we can compose them. Ask the SLAT store:
*which poems in sonnet form use their volta as
falsification?* The store returns Ozymandias. Ask: *which
poems make claims that can be tested against time?* Also
returns Ozymandias.

The composition is what makes the corpus a corpus rather
than a stack of documents. Each record contributes some
structure. The records reference each other. The runtime reading
them gets not just the individual pieces but the web they
form together.

## The pattern for adding more poems

For every sketch in the words book, an author can create a
poem record if they want. The record is optional. The
sketch is enough on its own. But for particularly
well-worked examples the record makes the poem searchable
alongside its form.

The rule is: authors don't have to make records for every
poem. They should make records for at least one poem per
form, so the form records have exemplars linked. Beyond
that, add records for poems that are especially
representative or especially instructive.

